Below is a **complete, self‑contained binding** that you can copy‑paste into a single directory, compile with `ocamlopt` (or `ocamlc`) and link against the BlockSci C++ library.  

It contains  

* the **public OCaml interface** (`blocksci.mli`) – what an OCaml user will see,  
* the **C‑C++ stub** (`blocksci_stubs.c`) – the glue that talks to the BlockSci iterator, and  
* a tiny **make‑file snippet** (commented at the top) that shows how to build the library.

The design follows the familiar “`iter`/`iteri`” pattern used by `Array`, `Seq`, Pandas, Polars … – the hot loop lives in C++ and only a *single* OCaml value (the `block` record) is allocated per iteration.  The callback is invoked via `caml_callback_exn`, so any OCaml exception aborts the walk and is propagated back to the caller.

---

## 1. Public OCaml API – `blocksci.mli`

```ocaml
(*----------------------------------------------------------------------
   blocksci.mli –  OCaml interface for the BlockSci C++ iterator
   ----------------------------------------------------------------------*)

(** A single Bitcoin block.  Only the fields that are cheap to copy are
    exposed; more can be added later without breaking the ABI. *)
type block = {
  height    : int;          (** Block height (0‑based) *)
  hash      : string;       (** Hex string of the block hash *)
  timestamp : int64;        (** Unix epoch time (seconds) *)
  tx_count  : int;          (** Number of transactions in the block *)
}

(** Opaque iterator over the whole blockchain.  The iterator is created
    once and can be reused many times.  It is a custom block with a finaliser
    that deletes the underlying C++ object, so the OCaml value can be
    freely GC‑collected. *)
type iterator

(** Create a new iterator that walks the whole chain from genesis to the
    current tip.  The iterator holds a pointer to the native BlockSci
    object, so it must be finalised. *)
val create : unit -> iterator

(** Reset the iterator to the beginning (genesis block).  This is cheap
    – it merely rewinds the underlying C++ iterator. *)
val reset : iterator -> unit

(** Return the next block, or [None] when the end of the chain is reached.
    The returned [block] value is freshly allocated each call. *)
val next : iterator -> block option

(** Iterate over *all* blocks, calling the supplied function for each
    block.  The callback runs in the C++ loop, therefore this is the
    fastest possible path.  If the callback raises an exception, the walk
    aborts and the exception is re‑raised in OCaml. *)
val iter : iterator -> (block -> unit) -> unit

(** Same as [iter] but also supplies the zero‑based index of the block
    (the height).  The extra index is cheap because the iterator already
    knows it. *)
val iteri : iterator -> (int -> block -> unit) -> unit
```

